stages.prompt_template:
Run prove-it-prototype for the feature specified at: {task}

RUN DIRECTORY = the directory that contains {task} (dirname of the spec path). All handoff files below live there; '<rundir>/' refers to it.

Read the signed spec. Do the 5-minute tracker search for prior art. State the smallest factual question the feature answers, write a <=50-line probe against the REAL codebase (not a fixture), define an INDEPENDENT oracle (a different mechanism than the probe — grep/jq/git/cargo tree/hand count), run both, and compare item by item. Expand by one question at a time until you trust the ground truth. Write probe.* and an Oracle section + a one-sentence 'what I learned' to <rundir>/ following prove-it-prototype's output contract; record progress in <rundir>/status.md. DECISION: if probe and oracle AGREE on a non-trivial slice, call summary(resultType='terminal') with a normal handoff report. If they DISAGREE and it is not your probe/oracle being wrong (i.e. the substrate is suspect), write the token HALT_FALSIFIED to <rundir>/status.md with the disagreeing items + suspected cause, file/point-to a tracker issue, and call summary(resultType='terminal') echoing HALT_FALSIFIED. Do NOT design, plan, or write feature code.

Run falsifiable-design for the feature specified at: {task}

RUN DIRECTORY = the directory that contains {task} (dirname of the spec path); '<rundir>/' refers to it.

FIRST read <rundir>/status.md; if it contains HALT_FALSIFIED, do nothing except call summary(resultType='terminal') re-echoing the halt reason. Otherwise: re-read the probe, enumerate every production-reachable input shape, run the subtractive-change / removed-invariant sweep, write the design as numbered one-sentence claims, and pair EACH claim with a falsifier (independent oracle, named buggy implementation that would trip it, distinct per-claim output, and a Regression fence). Rank falsifiers by cost and RUN THE CHEAPEST ONE NOW. Write <rundir>/design.md with the ## Falsification table (incl. Regression fence column) + a Negative space list (>=3). Honor the tracker discipline for every deferral. DECISION: if the cheapest falsifier PASSES and the hard gate is satisfied, call summary(resultType='terminal') with a handoff report. If the cheapest falsifier FAILS, the design is wrong — write HALT_FALSIFIED to <rundir>/status.md with the failing claim + result, and call summary(resultType='terminal') echoing it. Do NOT write a plan or feature code.

Run budgeted-plan for the feature specified at: {task}

RUN DIRECTORY = the directory that contains {task} (dirname of the spec path); '<rundir>/' refers to it.

FIRST read <rundir>/status.md; if it contains HALT_FALSIFIED, do nothing except call summary(resultType='terminal') re-echoing the halt reason. Otherwise: decompose the design's claim list into slices (each <=~50 LOC / <=2 files / <=30 min). For each slice fill ALL mandatory fields — Claim, Oracle, Stress fixture (designed to fail a plausible bug, expected output written BEFORE impl), Loop budget (asymptotic cost AND production scale), Wall budget if always-on, Files (the slice's planned file set — the build stage uses this to decide whether a fix stays in-slice). Apply the doc-comment-as-contract and output-stream rules. Run the five self-review lists; the plan is not done with gaps. Write <rundir>/plan.md following budgeted-plan's output contract. Honor the tracker discipline. Do NOT write feature code.
